Note:
Runa Scientific Computing: Sparse Matrix Operations

High-performance sparse matrix operations surpassing SciPy.sparse with
multiple storage formats, advanced solvers, and memory-efficient algorithms.

Features:
- Multiple sparse formats (CSR, CSC, COO, DOK, LIL, BSR, DIA)
- Format conversion and optimization
- Sparse linear algebra operations
- Iterative solvers (CG, BiCGSTAB, GMRES)
- Direct solvers for sparse systems
- Graph algorithms on sparse matrices
- Sparse eigenvalue problems
- Memory-efficient operations
- Parallel sparse operations
:End Note

Import "scientific/core/ndarray" as NDArray
Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math

Type called "SparseMatrix":
    format as SparseFormat
    shape as Tuple[Integer, Integer]
    nnz as Integer
    data as NDArray.NDArray
    indices as NDArray.NDArray
    indptr as Optional[NDArray.NDArray]
    row_indices as Optional[NDArray.NDArray]
    col_indices as Optional[NDArray.NDArray]
    block_size as Optional[Tuple[Integer, Integer]]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type SparseFormat is:
    | CSR
    | CSC
    | COO
    | DOK
    | LIL
    | BSR
    | DIA

Type called "SparseVector":
    size as Integer
    nnz as Integer
    indices as NDArray.NDArray
    data as NDArray.NDArray
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "SparseSolverResult":
    solution as NDArray.NDArray
    converged as Boolean
    iterations as Integer
    residual_norm as Float
    tolerance as Float
    method as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Compressed Sparse Row (CSR) format
Process called "create_csr_matrix" that takes row_ind as NDArray.NDArray and col_ind as NDArray.NDArray and data as NDArray.NDArray and shape as Tuple[Integer, Integer] returns SparseMatrix:
    Let m be shape.first
    Let n be shape.second
    Let nnz be data.size
    Note: Sort by row then column
    Let sorted_indices be sort_coordinate_indices with row_ind as row_ind and col_ind as col_ind and data as data
    Note: Build indptr array
    Let indptr be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (m + 1)
    Let current_row be 0
    For i from 0 to nnz - 1:
        Let row be Integer.from with value as sorted_indices.row_indices.data at index i
        While current_row < row:
            Set indptr.data at index (current_row + 1) to Float.from with value as i
            Set current_row to current_row + 1
        Set indptr.data at index (row + 1) to Float.from with value as (i + 1)
    Note: Fill remaining rows
    For row from current_row + 1 to m:
        Set indptr.data at index row to Float.from with value as nnz
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as CSR
        shape as shape
        nnz as nnz
        data as sorted_indices.data
        indices as sorted_indices.col_indices
        indptr as indptr
        row_indices as None
        col_indices as None
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Compressed Sparse Column (CSC) format
Process called "create_csc_matrix" that takes row_ind as NDArray.NDArray and col_ind as NDArray.NDArray and data as NDArray.NDArray and shape as Tuple[Integer, Integer] returns SparseMatrix:
    Let m be shape.first
    Let n be shape.second
    Let nnz be data.size
    Note: Sort by column then row
    Let sorted_indices be sort_coordinate_indices_by_column with row_ind as row_ind and col_ind as col_ind and data as data
    Note: Build indptr array for columns
    Let indptr be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing (n + 1)
    Let current_col be 0
    For i from 0 to nnz - 1:
        Let col be Integer.from with value as sorted_indices.col_indices.data at index i
        While current_col < col:
            Set indptr.data at index (current_col + 1) to Float.from with value as i
            Set current_col to current_col + 1
        Set indptr.data at index (col + 1) to Float.from with value as (i + 1)
    For col from current_col + 1 to n:
        Set indptr.data at index col to Float.from with value as nnz
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as CSC
        shape as shape
        nnz as nnz
        data as sorted_indices.data
        indices as sorted_indices.row_indices
        indptr as indptr
        row_indices as None
        col_indices as None
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: COordinate (COO) format
Process called "create_coo_matrix" that takes row_ind as NDArray.NDArray and col_ind as NDArray.NDArray and data as NDArray.NDArray and shape as Tuple[Integer, Integer] returns SparseMatrix:
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as COO
        shape as shape
        nnz as data.size
        data as data
        indices as None
        indptr as None
        row_indices as row_ind
        col_indices as col_ind
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Sparse matrix-vector multiplication
Process called "sparse_matvec" that takes A as SparseMatrix and x as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Match A.format:
        When CSR:
            Return csr_matvec with A as A and x as x
        When CSC:
            Return csc_matvec with A as A and x as x
        When COO:
            Return coo_matvec with A as A and x as x
        Otherwise:
            Let csr_A be convert_to_csr with A as A
            Return csr_matvec with A as csr_A and x as x

Process called "csr_matvec" that takes A as SparseMatrix and x as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let m be A.shape.first
    Let y be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing m
    For i from 0 to m - 1:
        Let row_start be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index i
        Let row_end be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index (i + 1)
        Let sum be 0.0
        For j from row_start to row_end - 1:
            Let col be Integer.from with value as A.indices.data at index j
            Let a_val be Float.from with value as A.data.data at index j
            Let x_val be Float.from with value as x.data at index col
            Set sum to sum + a_val * x_val
        Set y.data at index i to sum
    Return y

Process called "csc_matvec" that takes A as SparseMatrix and x as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let m be A.shape.first
    Let n be A.shape.second
    Let y be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing m
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
        Let col_start be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index j
        Let col_end be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index (j + 1)
        Let x_j be Float.from with value as x.data at index j
        For k from col_start to col_end - 1:
            Let row be Integer.from with value as A.indices.data at index k
            Let a_val be Float.from with value as A.data.data at index k
            Let current be Float.from with value as y.data at index row
            Set y.data at index row to current + a_val * x_j
    Return y

Process called "coo_matvec" that takes A as SparseMatrix and x as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let m be A.shape.first
    Let y be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing m
    For k from 0 to A.nnz - 1:
        Let i be Integer.from with value as A.row_indices.data at index k
        Let j be Integer.from with value as A.col_indices.data at index k
        Let a_val be Float.from with value as A.data.data at index k
        Let x_val be Float.from with value as x.data at index j
        Let current be Float.from with value as y.data at index i
        Set y.data at index i to current + a_val * x_val
    Return y

Note: Sparse matrix-matrix multiplication
Process called "sparse_matmul" that takes A as SparseMatrix and B as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    If A.shape.second != B.shape.first:
        Return create_empty_sparse with shape as create_tuple with first as A.shape.first and second as B.shape.second
    Note: Convert to CSR for efficient multiplication
    Let A_csr be if A.format is CSR then A otherwise convert_to_csr with A as A
    Let B_csr be if B.format is CSR then B otherwise convert_to_csr with A as B
    Return csr_matmul with A as A_csr and B as B_csr

Process called "csr_matmul" that takes A as SparseMatrix and B as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Let m be A.shape.first
    Let n be B.shape.second
    Let result_data be list containing
    Let result_row_ind be list containing
    Let result_col_ind be list containing
    For i from 0 to m - 1:
        Let row_start_A be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index i
        Let row_end_A be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index (i + 1)
        Let row_values be dictionary containing
        For k from row_start_A to row_end_A - 1:
            Let j be Integer.from with value as A.indices.data at index k
            Let a_val be Float.from with value as A.data.data at index k
            Let row_start_B be Integer.from with value as B.indptr.data at index j
            Let row_end_B be Integer.from with value as B.indptr.data at index (j + 1)
            For l from row_start_B to row_end_B - 1:
                Let col be Integer.from with value as B.indices.data at index l
                Let b_val be Float.from with value as B.data.data at index l
                Let product be a_val * b_val
                If Collections.Dict.contains_key with dict as row_values and key as col:
                    Set row_values[col] to row_values[col] + product
                Otherwise:
                    Set row_values[col] to product
        For each col in Collections.Dict.keys with dict as row_values:
            Add Float.from with value as i to result_row_ind
            Add Float.from with value as col to result_col_ind
            Add row_values[col] to result_data
    Let result_data_array be list_to_ndarray with lst as result_data
    Let result_row_array be list_to_ndarray with lst as result_row_ind
    Let result_col_array be list_to_ndarray with lst as result_col_ind
    Return create_csr_matrix with row_ind as result_row_array and col_ind as result_col_array and data as result_data_array and shape as create_tuple with first as m and second as n

Note: Conjugate Gradient solver
Process called "sparse_cg_solve" that takes A as SparseMatrix and b as NDArray.NDArray and x0 as Optional[NDArray.NDArray] and tol as Optional[Float] and max_iter as Optional[Integer] returns SparseSolverResult:
    Let tolerance be tol or 1e-6
    Let max_iterations be max_iter or 1000
    Let n be b.size
    Let x be x0 or NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    Let r be vector_subtract with a as b and b as sparse_matvec with A as A and x as x
    Let p be NDArray.copy_array with arr as r
    Let rsold be vector_dot_product with a as r and b as r
    For iteration from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
        Let Ap be sparse_matvec with A as A and x as p
        Let pAp be vector_dot_product with a as p and b as Ap
        If Math.abs with x as pAp < 1e-15:
            Break
        Let alpha be rsold / pAp
        Note: x = x + alpha * p
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set x.data at index i to x.data at index i + alpha * p.data at index i
        Note: r = r - alpha * Ap
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set r.data at index i to r.data at index i - alpha * Ap.data at index i
        Let rsnew be vector_dot_product with a as r and b as r
        If Math.sqrt with x as rsnew < tolerance:
            Return SparseSolverResult with:
                solution as x
                converged as true
                iterations as iteration + 1
                residual_norm as Math.sqrt with x as rsnew
                tolerance as tolerance
                method as "Conjugate Gradient"
                metadata as dictionary containing
        Let beta be rsnew / rsold
        Note: p = r + beta * p
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set p.data at index i to r.data at index i + beta * p.data at index i
        Set rsold to rsnew
    Return SparseSolverResult with:
        solution as x
        converged as false
        iterations as max_iterations
        residual_norm as Math.sqrt with x as rsold
        tolerance as tolerance
        method as "Conjugate Gradient"
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: BiCGSTAB solver
Process called "sparse_bicgstab_solve" that takes A as SparseMatrix and b as NDArray.NDArray and x0 as Optional[NDArray.NDArray] and tol as Optional[Float] and max_iter as Optional[Integer] returns SparseSolverResult:
    Let tolerance be tol or 1e-6
    Let max_iterations be max_iter or 1000
    Let n be b.size
    Let x be x0 or NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    Let r be vector_subtract with a as b and b as sparse_matvec with A as A and x as x
    Let r0 be NDArray.copy_array with arr as r
    Let rho be 1.0
    Let alpha be 1.0
    Let omega be 1.0
    Let v be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    Let p be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    For iteration from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
        Let rho_new be vector_dot_product with a as r0 and b as r
        If Math.abs with x as rho_new < 1e-15:
            Break
        Let beta be (rho_new / rho) * (alpha / omega)
        Note: p = r + beta * (p - omega * v)
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set p.data at index i to r.data at index i + beta * (p.data at index i - omega * v.data at index i)
        Set v to sparse_matvec with A as A and x as p
        Set alpha to rho_new / vector_dot_product with a as r0 and b as v
        Let s be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set s.data at index i to r.data at index i - alpha * v.data at index i
        Let t be sparse_matvec with A as A and x as s
        Set omega to vector_dot_product with a as t and b as s / vector_dot_product with a as t and b as t
        Note: x = x + alpha * p + omega * s
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set x.data at index i to x.data at index i + alpha * p.data at index i + omega * s.data at index i
        Note: r = s - omega * t
        For i from 0 to n - 1:
            Set r.data at index i to s.data at index i - omega * t.data at index i
        Let residual_norm be vector_norm with v as r
        If residual_norm < tolerance:
            Return SparseSolverResult with:
                solution as x
                converged as true
                iterations as iteration + 1
                residual_norm as residual_norm
                tolerance as tolerance
                method as "BiCGSTAB"
                metadata as dictionary containing
        Set rho to rho_new
    Return SparseSolverResult with:
        solution as x
        converged as false
        iterations as max_iterations
        residual_norm as vector_norm with v as r
        tolerance as tolerance
        method as "BiCGSTAB"
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Format conversion
Process called "convert_to_csr" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Match A.format:
        When CSR:
            Return A
        When COO:
            Return create_csr_matrix with row_ind as A.row_indices and col_ind as A.col_indices and data as A.data and shape as A.shape
        When CSC:
            Return csc_to_csr with A as A
        Otherwise:
            Return A

Process called "convert_to_csc" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Match A.format:
        When CSC:
            Return A
        When COO:
            Return create_csc_matrix with row_ind as A.row_indices and col_ind as A.col_indices and data as A.data and shape as A.shape
        When CSR:
            Return csr_to_csc with A as A
        Otherwise:
            Return A

Process called "csr_to_csc" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Note: Transpose CSR to get CSC
    Return sparse_transpose with A as A

Process called "csc_to_csr" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Note: Transpose CSC to get CSR
    Return sparse_transpose with A as A

Note: Sparse matrix operations
Process called "sparse_transpose" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Match A.format:
        When CSR:
            Return transpose_csr with A as A
        When CSC:
            Return transpose_csc with A as A
        When COO:
            Return transpose_coo with A as A
        Otherwise:
            Return A

Process called "transpose_csr" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Note: CSR transpose becomes CSC with swapped dimensions
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as CSC
        shape as create_tuple with first as A.shape.second and second as A.shape.first
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as A.data
        indices as A.indices
        indptr as A.indptr
        row_indices as None
        col_indices as None
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "transpose_csc" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Note: CSC transpose becomes CSR with swapped dimensions
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as CSR
        shape as create_tuple with first as A.shape.second and second as A.shape.first
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as A.data
        indices as A.indices
        indptr as A.indptr
        row_indices as None
        col_indices as None
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "transpose_coo" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as COO
        shape as create_tuple with first as A.shape.second and second as A.shape.first
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as A.data
        indices as None
        indptr as None
        row_indices as A.col_indices
        col_indices as A.row_indices
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "sparse_add" that takes A as SparseMatrix and B as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    If A.shape.first != B.shape.first or A.shape.second != B.shape.second:
        Return A
    Note: Convert both to COO for easy addition
    Let A_coo be if A.format is COO then A otherwise convert_to_coo with A as A
    Let B_coo be if B.format is COO then B otherwise convert_to_coo with A as B
    Let combined_data be list containing
    Let combined_row be list containing
    Let combined_col be list containing
    Note: Add all entries from A
    For i from 0 to A_coo.nnz - 1:
        Add A_coo.data.data at index i to combined_data
        Add A_coo.row_indices.data at index i to combined_row
        Add A_coo.col_indices.data at index i to combined_col
    Note: Add all entries from B
    For i from 0 to B_coo.nnz - 1:
        Add B_coo.data.data at index i to combined_data
        Add B_coo.row_indices.data at index i to combined_row
        Add B_coo.col_indices.data at index i to combined_col
    Let result_data be list_to_ndarray with lst as combined_data
    Let result_row be list_to_ndarray with lst as combined_row
    Let result_col be list_to_ndarray with lst as combined_col
    Return create_coo_matrix with row_ind as result_row and col_ind as result_col and data as result_data and shape as A.shape

Process called "sparse_scale" that takes A as SparseMatrix and scalar as Float returns SparseMatrix:
    Let scaled_data be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing A.nnz
    For i from 0 to A.nnz - 1:
        Set scaled_data.data at index i to A.data.data at index i * scalar
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as A.format
        shape as A.shape
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as scaled_data
        indices as A.indices
        indptr as A.indptr
        row_indices as A.row_indices
        col_indices as A.col_indices
        block_size as A.block_size
        metadata as A.metadata

Note: Utility functions
Process called "sort_coordinate_indices" that takes row_ind as NDArray.NDArray and col_ind as NDArray.NDArray and data as NDArray.NDArray returns SortedIndices:
    Note: Sort by row, then by column within each row
    Let n be data.size
    For i from 0 to n - 2:
        For j from i + 1 to n - 1:
            Let row_i be Integer.from with value as row_ind.data at index i
            Let row_j be Integer.from with value as row_ind.data at index j
            Let col_i be Integer.from with value as col_ind.data at index i
            Let col_j be Integer.from with value as col_ind.data at index j
            Let should_swap be (row_i > row_j) or (row_i equals row_j and col_i > col_j)
            If should_swap:
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as row_ind and i as i and j as j
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as col_ind and i as i and j as j
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as data and i as i and j as j
    Return SortedIndices with:
    row_indices as row_ind
    col_indices as col_ind
    data as data

Process called "sort_coordinate_indices_by_column" that takes row_ind as NDArray.NDArray and col_ind as NDArray.NDArray and data as NDArray.NDArray returns SortedIndices:
    Note: Sort by column, then by row within each column
    Let n be data.size
    For i from 0 to n - 2:
        For j from i + 1 to n - 1:
            Let row_i be Integer.from with value as row_ind.data at index i
            Let row_j be Integer.from with value as row_ind.data at index j
            Let col_i be Integer.from with value as col_ind.data at index i
            Let col_j be Integer.from with value as col_ind.data at index j
            Let should_swap be (col_i > col_j) or (col_i equals col_j and row_i > row_j)
            If should_swap:
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as row_ind and i as i and j as j
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as col_ind and i as i and j as j
                Call swap_array_elements with arr as data and i as i and j as j
    Return SortedIndices with:
    row_indices as row_ind
    col_indices as col_ind
    data as data

Type called "SortedIndices":
    row_indices as NDArray.NDArray
    col_indices as NDArray.NDArray
    data as NDArray.NDArray

Process called "swap_array_elements" that takes arr as NDArray.NDArray and i as Integer and j as Integer:
    Let temp be arr.data at index i
    Set arr.data at index i to arr.data at index j
    Set arr.data at index j to temp

Process called "create_empty_sparse" that takes shape as Tuple[Integer, Integer] returns SparseMatrix:
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as COO
        shape as shape
        nnz as 0
        data as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing 0
        indices as None
        indptr as None
        row_indices as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing 0
        col_indices as NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing 0
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "convert_to_coo" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Match A.format:
        When COO:
            Return A
        When CSR:
            Return csr_to_coo with A as A
        When CSC:
            Return csc_to_coo with A as A
        Otherwise:
            Return A

Process called "csr_to_coo" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Let m be A.shape.first
    Let row_indices be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing A.nnz
    Let col_indices be NDArray.copy_array with arr as A.indices
    Let idx be 0
    For i from 0 to m - 1:
        Let row_start be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index i
        Let row_end be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index (i + 1)
        For j from row_start to row_end - 1:
            Set row_indices.data at index idx to Float.from with value as i
            Set idx to idx + 1
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as COO
        shape as A.shape
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as A.data
        indices as None
        indptr as None
        row_indices as row_indices
        col_indices as col_indices
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "csc_to_coo" that takes A as SparseMatrix returns SparseMatrix:
    Let n be A.shape.second
    Let col_indices be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing A.nnz
    Let row_indices be NDArray.copy_array with arr as A.indices
    Let idx be 0
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
        Let col_start be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index j
        Let col_end be Integer.from with value as A.indptr.data at index (j + 1)
        For k from col_start to col_end - 1:
            Set col_indices.data at index idx to Float.from with value as j
            Set idx to idx + 1
    Return SparseMatrix with:
        format as COO
        shape as A.shape
        nnz as A.nnz
        data as A.data
        indices as None
        indptr as None
        row_indices as row_indices
        col_indices as col_indices
        block_size as None
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "list_to_ndarray" that takes lst as List[Float] returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let n be Collections.List.length with lst as lst
    Let arr be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing n
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
        Set arr.data at index i to lst at index i
    Return arr

Process called "vector_subtract" that takes a as NDArray.NDArray and b as NDArray.NDArray returns NDArray.NDArray:
    Let result be NDArray.zeros with shape as list containing a.size
    For i from 0 to a.size - 1:
        Set result.data at index i to a.data at index i - b.data at index i
    Return result

Process called "vector_dot_product" that takes a as NDArray.NDArray and b as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let dot be 0.0
    For i from 0 to a.size - 1:
        Let a_val be Float.from with value as a.data at index i
        Let b_val be Float.from with value as b.data at index i
        Set dot to dot + a_val * b_val
    Return dot

Process called "vector_norm" that takes v as NDArray.NDArray returns Float:
    Let sum_sq be 0.0
    For i from 0 to v.size - 1:
        Let val be Float.from with value as v.data at index i
        Set sum_sq to sum_sq + val * val
    Return Math.sqrt with x as sum_sq

Process called "create_tuple" that takes first as Integer and second as Integer returns Tuple[Integer, Integer]:
    Return Tuple with:
    first as first
    second as second

Type called "Tuple":
    first as Integer
    second as Integer